question:
Let $S$ be a set of rational numbers such that
\begin{enumerate}
\item[(a)] $0 \in S$;
\item[(b)] If $x \in S$ then $x+1\in S$ and $x-1\in S$; and
\item[(c)] If $x\in S$ and $x\not\in\{0,1\}$, then $\frac{1}{x(x-1)}\in S$.
\end{enumerate}
Must $S$ contain all rational numbers?

